m to explore the often surprising encounters among religious traditions that the Middle Ages afforded. This collection of essays works through what was known of the Qur'an and of Islamic philosophy and science in Dante's day and explores the bases for Dante's images of Muhammad and Ali. It further compels us to look at key instances of engagement among Muslims, Jews, and Christians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslamxHistory. 0aIslam and literaturexHistory. 0aIslam in literature. 0aIslamxRelationsxChristianityxHistory. 0aIslamic philosophyxIn literature. 4aDante. 4aIslam. 4aMuhammad. 4aMuslim-Christian. 4aNight Voyage. 4aOrientalism. 4aconvivencia. 4ami'raj. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Italian.2bisacsh1 aZiolkowski, Jan M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082326389940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823263899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823263899.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK